# Unity UI Canvas (UGUI) Rules

## Project Policy (This Project)

- Per `[.cursor/rules/project-overview.mdc]`, **new UI in this project uses Unity UI Canvas / UGUI as the primary stack**, with **TextMeshPro for all text**.
- UI Toolkit is optional and may be used only when explicitly specified for a given feature or demo.
- Other projects may explicitly choose a different UI stack in their own `project-overview.mdc`, in which case their overview overrides these defaults.

This rule applies when implementing or editing UI that uses **Unity UI (Canvas / uGUI)** — the GameObject-based system using `UnityEngine.UI`, Canvas, and RectTransform. For UI Toolkit (UXML/USS), see **unity-ui-toolkit.mdc**.

---

## Project Structure

Use the same layout as code-organization: UI under `Assets/Scripts/Runtime/UI/`. For Canvas-based UI, typical subfolders:

```
Assets/
└── Scripts/
    └── Runtime/
        └── UI/
            ├── Controllers/      # MonoBehaviour controllers for screens/panels
            ├── Views/            # Optional view components
            └── Prefabs/          # Reference from Prefabs/UI/ in Project window
```

Prefabs for Canvas UI live under `Assets/Prefabs/UI/` (per code-organization).

---

## Canvas & Render Modes

- **Canvas** is the abstract space for all UI; every UI element must be under a GameObject with a Canvas component.
- **Render Mode** (Canvas component):
  - **Screen Space - Overlay**: Renders on top of the scene; Canvas resizes with screen. No camera.
  - **Screen Space - Camera**: UI at a set distance in front of a **Camera**; camera settings (e.g. FOV) affect the UI. Set **Render Camera** and **Plane Distance**.
  - **World Space**: Canvas is a 3D object in the scene; size via RectTransform. Use for in-world/diegetic UI. Set **Event Camera** for UI events.
- **Pixel Perfect** (Screen Space modes): Optional; disables antialiasing for sharp pixels.
- **Receives Events**: Enable so this Canvas gets input (GraphicRaycaster required).

---

## Canvas Scaler (Multi-Resolution)

- Add **Canvas Scaler** to the root Canvas when using Screen Space modes.
- **Constant Pixel Size**: No scaling; same pixel size on all resolutions (rarely ideal).
- **Scale With Screen Size**: Recommended. Set a **Reference Resolution** (e.g. 1920×1080 or target device). Canvas scales to match screen; use **Screen Match Mode** (Match Width Or Height, Expand, Shrink) and **Match** (0 = width, 1 = height, 0.5 = balance) to control aspect-ratio behavior.
- Test at multiple **aspect ratios** (portrait vs landscape); adjust **Match** (e.g. 0.5) so layout doesn’t over-scale on one axis.

---

## RectTransform & Layout

- **RectTransform**: Used for all UI elements. Defines **anchors** (min/max as fraction of parent), **pivot**, **position**, **width/height** (or left/top/right/bottom when anchors are split).
- **Anchors**: Define how the rect sticks to the parent (corners, edges, stretch). Use **Shift** while dragging anchor to move the corner with it.
- Prefer **Layout Groups** (HorizontalLayoutGroup, VerticalLayoutGroup, GridLayoutGroup) plus **LayoutElement** / **ContentSizeFitter** for dynamic layouts instead of manual positioning where possible.
- To force a layout recalculation from code: `LayoutRebuilder.MarkLayoutForRebuild(rectTransform);` (queued to end of frame).

---

## Core Components (UnityEngine.UI + TextMeshPro)

- **Graphic** (base): Image, RawImage, TMP_Text. Required for raycast and batching.
- **Image**: Sprites or simple color; supports **Raycast Target** (turn off when not clickable to reduce raycast cost).
- **Text (legacy)**: **Do not use**. All UI text in this project (including migrated/legacy UIs) must use **TextMeshPro - Text (UI)** (`TMPro.TextMeshProUGUI`) instead of `UnityEngine.UI.Text`. Any existing legacy `Text` components **must be converted** to TextMeshPro using Unity's TMP conversion tools, and the UI should be **manually tested afterwards** to verify layout, localization, and formatting still behave correctly.
- **Button, Toggle, Slider, Scrollbar, InputField, Dropdown**: Built-in controls; use **onClick** / **onValueChanged** or implement **IPointerClickHandler**, **IDragHandler**, etc., on custom components.
- **Mask** vs **RectMask2D**: RectMask2D has better performance (no stencil); use it when a rectangular clip is enough. Mask uses image alpha and is more expensive; use only when you need non-rectangular masking.

---

## Event System & Input

- **EventSystem**: One per scene; manages input modules and event queue. Required for UI input.
- **StandaloneInputModule**: Handles mouse and keyboard; works with **GraphicRaycaster** (on Canvas) to determine what’s under the pointer.
- **GraphicRaycaster**: On each Canvas; raycasts against Graphics to resolve clicks/touches. Can ignore backfacing graphics and respect 2D/3D blockers.
- Use **ExecuteEvents** and interfaces (**IPointerClickHandler**, **IDragHandler**, **IPointerDownHandler**, etc.) for custom event handling.
- Only one **EventSystem** should be active per scene; avoid duplicates.

---

## Performance: Do’s and Don’ts

### Do

- Use **RectMask2D** instead of **Mask** when a rectangle clip is sufficient (better performance).
- Set **Raycast Target** to **false** on non-interactive Graphics (Images, Text) to reduce raycast cost.
- Keep **Canvas** hierarchy flat where possible; nested Canvases each have their own rebuild/batch.
- Use the **UI** and **UI Details** Profiler modules to inspect batches, vertices, and rebuild cost.
- Prefer **LayoutGroup** + **ContentSizeFitter** and avoid forcing **MarkLayoutForRebuild** every frame.
- Use **Canvas Scaler > Scale With Screen Size** with a fixed reference resolution and test multiple aspect ratios.
- Cache **RectTransform** and **Graphic** references; avoid repeated **GetComponent** or **Find** in Update.

### Don’t

- Don’t use **Mask** when **RectMask2D** can do the job (stencil cost).
- Don’t leave **Raycast Target** on for decorative Images/Text that don’t need input.
- Don’t create multiple **EventSystem** instances in the same scene.
- Don’t nest Canvases unnecessarily; each Canvas has rebuild and batching overhead.
- Don’t rely only on one resolution or aspect ratio; test **Canvas Scaler** with different **Match** values (e.g. 0.5 for balanced scaling).
- Don’t call **MarkLayoutForRebuild** repeatedly in the same frame; it’s queued and processed once per frame.

---

## Best Practices Checklist

### Setup
- One **Canvas** per “screen” or major UI block; use **Canvas Scaler** with **Scale With Screen Size** and a clear reference resolution.
- One **EventSystem** per scene; **GraphicRaycaster** on each Canvas that receives input.
- Choose **Render Mode** intentionally: Overlay (simple HUD), Camera (world-relative 2D UI), World Space (in-world UI).

### Layout
- Use **anchors** for responsive behavior; avoid hard-coded pixel positions where the UI must scale.
- Prefer **LayoutGroup** + **LayoutElement** / **ContentSizeFitter** for lists and dynamic content.
- Use **RectMask2D** for scroll/clip regions instead of **Mask** when possible.

### Code
- Cache **RectTransform** and **Graphic** references in **Awake**; avoid **GetComponent** in **Update**.
- Unsubscribe from **Button.onClick** / **onValueChanged** in **OnDestroy** to avoid leaks.
- Use **SerializeField** private fields for Canvas/UI references; avoid **Find** at runtime.

### Performance
- **Raycast Target** off on non-interactive Graphics.
- Minimize deep hierarchy and nested Canvases; use Profiler to check UI batches and rebuilds.
- Prefer object pooling for frequently instantiated UI elements (e.g. list items).

### Naming & Conventions
- Follow project C# conventions: `_camelCase` for private fields, PascalCase for types and public members.
- Name Canvas roots and panels clearly (e.g. `Canvas_HUD`, `Panel_MainMenu`).
